[00:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'I fixed lyrics, changed a singer\'s voice, and even swapped a chorus. All using Sunno\'s new editing features. Yes, you heard it right. With Sunno\'s latest updates, you can modify songs after they\'ve already been generated. You can'

[00:13] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'tweak lyrics, adjust sections, and even change or recreate the voice, all without starting from scratch. So, in this video, I\'ll show you how to use these new Sunno AI features so that you can get more control over your generated'

[00:27] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'songs. You\'ll find links to all the exclusive discounts in the description below. First, let\'s look at how to change lyrics using the replace section. Open the song from either create or library. Click the three dot menu. Go to'

[00:40] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'edit and click replace section. Once inside, select the portion of the song you want to change. The original lyrics will autofill, giving you a starting point for your edits. From here, you can'

[00:53] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'either let suggest alternatives or manually edit the lyrics yourself. After making your changes, click the replace section, and Sunno will generate two new versions of the song. You can then'

[01:05] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'select the one you like best and the tool will regenerate the full song with the new sections seamlessly integrated. For better results, always verify the original lyrics before editing. You can use the smart selection option in most'

[01:19] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'cases. However, for shorter sections, it\'s better to use fixed selection. Classic selection is better for longer sections. This helps keep transitions smooth and fluent while giving you more'

[01:31] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'control over the selected range. Here\'s a pro tip to make editing chorus lyrics more efficient. Instead of replacing each chorus individually, replace just the master chorus first. Then duplicate that replaced chorus as many times as'

[01:45] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'needed, depending on the number of choruses in your track. After that, [music] delete the original chorus sections and rearrange the duplicated ones into their correct positions. This method keeps your original audio safe'

[01:59] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'while ensuring all choruses are updated consistently without extra work or unnecessary credit usage. For users on the free plan, Sunno offers the reuse prompt feature which allows you to'

[02:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'recreate a song while keeping editable fields. To use it, click the three dot menu on the song you want to edit. Then go to edit and choose use styles and lyrics. From there, you can modify the'

[02:24] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'lyrics or change the music style. Once you generate a new version, Sunno produces a different audio rendition of the song with your updated lyrics. This method works best for larger rewrites'

[02:36] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'such as changing the chorus or reimagining entire verses rather than making small targeted lyric fixes. Next, let\'s see how to change the ending of a song using extend. This feature allows'

[02:48] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'you to replace the entire ending of a song. You can choose exactly where the original track stops and then Sunno generates a new continuation from that point. You can extend your track by'

[03:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'clicking the three dots, selecting extend, choosing the range, adding your lyrics and style, and then hitting create. This allows you to generate the extended part separately. If you want'

[03:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the extension attached directly to the song, you can do it inside the editor. Click the arrow at the end, select the range, generate, and then choose the best option from the alternatives. This'

[03:24] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'is especially useful for adding new verses, changing the outro, or creating mood shifts at the end of a track. Now, let\'s explore the different ways to change the voice of your song. The first method is recreate with style and'

[03:38] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'lyrics. Go to remix, click edit, then select use style and lyrics. Next, choose a male or female voice and describe the vocal style in the prompt.'

[03:50] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'This method works well, but the downside is that the song may change slightly more than you expect. The second method is cover version. You create a cover of your own song and adjust sliders such as'

[04:03] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'audio influence, weirdness, and style influence. This keeps the original song structure intact while changing the voice tone effectively. The third method is stem extraction, [music] which costs'

[04:15] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'credits. Here you extract the stems of the song, remove or replace the vocals externally, and optionally use third-party tools for full voice replacement. This approach is best if you want a completely different vocal or'

[04:28] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'a custom voice that isn\'t available in the built-in options. Before we wrap up, let\'s discuss pricing. The replace section feature is currently in early access beta, so it\'s available only to pro and premier users starting at $10'

[04:42] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'per month. But you can use the reuse prompt feature for free as said earlier. Overall, with tools like replace section, reuse prompt, extend, and voice editing workflows, you can finally get'

[04:56] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the granular level control that can transform your AI generated songs to the next level. So, try out Sunno AI\'s editing features using the discount link in the description and let me know about'

